structured.title: Planning Spring Baptism Service After Sermon
structured.overview: The group discusses logistics for an upcoming sermon on baptism and when to schedule actual baptisms afterward. The User plans to preach on baptism tomorrow and initially suggests May 17 (just after exams) for the baptisms, but others argue this is a bad time due to exam-related busyness and preparation demands. June is rejected as too far away, and they debate the tension between giving a concrete date during the sermon and the need to coordinate with key people (e.g., youth leaders like Ryan and Sarah, and regular church members such as Steve, Lois, Ben, Ellen, Richard, and Debbie) so they can attend. An alternative date of April 12, the Sunday after Easter, is floated but challenged because many people travel over Easter. In the end, the advice is not to announce a specific date during the sermon but instead to say that baptisms will happen "this spring," then first determine who wants to be baptized (youth vs adults) and check availability of core leaders and congregation members before fixing a date.

action_items.description: Coordinate with church leaders to choose a baptism date in spring

apps_results.content:
## Planning baptism sermon
- Preaching on baptism tomorrow, want linked baptism date  
- Initially suggested May 17, three days after exams  
- Concern raised: bad timing, heavy prep week after exams  

## Debating baptism timing
- Hesitation to delay to June; feels too far (6 months)  
- Wants date closer to sermon to keep momentum  
- Seeks help identifying a “sensible” earlier date  

## Considering alternative dates
- Idea: baptism after, not instead of, a service  
- Proposed April 12, Sunday after Easter, as option  
- Acknowledged some people travel over Easter holidays  

## Coordination with church and youth
- Need to involve Ryan for youth baptism readiness  
- Important to check availability of key leaders, core team  
- Number/type (youth vs adults) affects baptism planning  

## Final decision and communication
- Agreed: don’t announce a fixed date tomorrow  
- Instead say baptisms will be “this spring”  
- Will gauge interest first, then set a suitable date  

## Next steps
- Preach on baptism, invite interest for spring baptisms  
- Consult leaders’ calendars before fixing exact date  
- Meet potential candidates to assess readiness and plan format
